<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-911-720  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 911 720.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Nov 28 1989 v139 pB9(N) pC17(L) 18 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CD-ROM for the common man. (Personal Computers) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lewis, Peter H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Headstart Technologies Co will use CD-ROM drives in its newpersonal computers, the Headstart LX-CD and Headstart III-CD,signifying the first time home computers will use inexpensive CDtechnology.andP;  Prior to Headstart's mass marketing of thetechnology, CD-ROM was an expensive venture, with drives costingfrom $600 to $1,000.andP;  Because of economies of scale, Headstart'sCD-ROM drives will average $300 to $400.andP;  The LX-CD, $1,999, has768Kbytes of memory, a 40Mbyte hard disk, a 3.5 -inch diskettedrive, and a 5-inch CD-ROM drive.andP;  The III-CD, $2,999, offers amore powerful 80286 processor, 1Mbyte of memory and a 2,400-baudmodem.andP;  Both microcomputers come without monitors, which may bepurchased separately.andP;  Because CD-ROM technology is beginning toreach mass audiences, software publishers will attempt to lowerthe cost of programs, from several hundred dollars apiece to atarget of $50 to $100 per program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   North American Philips Corp. HeadStart Technologies Co. (productintroduction).andO;Product:   Headstart Technologies LX-CD (Microcomputer) (productintroduction)Headstart Technologies III-CD (Microcomputer) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     CD-ROMComputer industryMicrocomputersProduct Introduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>